>> "accsah" == accsah  <accsah@vaxa.hofstra.edu> writes:
In article <1993Aug29.193646.2845@vaxa> accsah@vaxa.hofstra.edu writes:


   accsah> In article <CCHI7M.8Mx@knot.ccs.queensu.ca>, hausner@qucis.queensu.ca (Alejo Hausner) writes:
   >> 
   >> Of course, there's thumb-prints and retinal patterns, but I'm
   >> trying to think of some method that doesn't use specialized
   >> hardware.  Perhaps some incident from childhood that only the
   >> user is aware of?  Some sort of personal detail, which would be
   >> spoken to the merchant?

   accsah> The simplest way I can think of is voice recognition.  If
   accsah> you can digitally scan the voice of the card holder with
   accsah> them saying a phrase, and then store it for later
   accsah> comparison, that is the most simplest way.  The only
   accsah> drawback I can see is, the certain amount of leaway in the
   accsah> checking algorithm, that would take care of poor phone
   accsah> transmissions.

What about a tape-recorded (or digitally recorded) version of the
person saying the phrase?  That should be fairly easy to obtain,
without the person's knowledge.  


